root_causes: Missing CompareNum3D validation: no check that SumA1x3 equals f('S7')['3'].toNumber() as required by ValidationCode.
Missing RequireCheck3D(CurrentForm()) call from ValidationCode.
Per-item validity incorrectly flags missing values as invalid (IF uses MISS(x) OR ~RANGE(x,0,999)) despite question attribute NotRequired=true.
DO REPEAT logic does not initialize the item flag before setting it (A1x3_itemFlag may be undefined for good cases).
SEL IF is used to filter cases for the 'Other' open-text consistency check instead of flagging/reporting them; this removes all other cases rather than marking inconsistencies.
Open-text consistency check uses string comparisons (A1x3_9_other = '' / <> '') without robust missing checks (should use MISSING() or TRIM checks depending on variable type).
No handling for special codes (e.g. 97, 98, 99) — these codes are not allowed/treated explicitly in range checks or in the SUM exclusion logic.
Sum computed (SumA1x3) but never compared to the target value (S7['3']), so AutoSum validation is not implemented.
instructions: Add the required validation calls at the start: call RequireCheck3D(CurrentForm()); and implement CompareNum3D('A1x3','=',f('S7')['3'].toNumber(),'defaults'); after computing SumA1x3 so the sum is validated against S7_3.

Change the per-item numeric validity IF to only validate non-missing responses: initialize flag (e.g. COMPUTE A1x3_itemFlag = 0.) then inside DO REPEAT use IF (NOT MISSING(x) AND NOT RANGE(x,0,999) AND x NOT IN (97,98,99)) A1x3_itemFlag = 1. This permits missing entries (NotRequired) and allows special codes if they should be allowed.
Initialize A1x3_itemFlag = 0 before the DO REPEAT loop and ensure the loop ends properly (use END REPEAT).

Replace SEL IF ... with a flagging statement for open-text consistency. For example: COMPUTE A1x3_otherFlag = 0. IF ((A1x3_9 > 0 AND (MISSING(A1x3_9_other) OR TRIM(A1x3_9_other) = '')) OR ((A1x3_9 = 0 OR MISSING(A1x3_9)) AND (NOT MISSING(A1x3_9_other) AND TRIM(A1x3_9_other) <> ''))) A1x3_otherFlag = 1. Then list or report flagged cases instead of selecting only them.
Use MISSING() or TRIM(...)= '' for open-text variable checks rather than comparing to an empty string literal alone, to handle both string empty and system-missing values correctly.

Decide how to treat special codes (97/98/99): if they should be allowed values, include them in the validity check (x IN (97,98,99)) or exclude them from the SUM computation (use SUM with ignore of those codes). Update SumA1x3 computation to exclude special codes if appropriate: e.g. SumA1x3 = SUM(RECODES to treat 97/98/99 as $SYSMIS) or use conditional sum: SUM( IF(x NOT IN (97,98,99), x, 0) ... ).
After computing SumA1x3, explicitly compare it to f('S7')['3'].toNumber() and set a validation flag if mismatch (e.g. IF (NOT MISSING(SumA1x3) AND SumA1x3 <> f('S7')['3') ) A1x3_sumFlag = 1).

root_causes: Missing the required sum comparison validation (CompareNum3D) comparing SumA1x4 to f('S7')['4'].toNumber().
Per-item numeric check treats missing cells as invalid (IF (MISS(x) OR ~RANGE(...))), but items are NotRequired so missing should be allowed.

SEL IF is used to enforce 'Other' open-text logic, which incorrectly drops cases instead of flagging/informing; also SEL IF expression logic is fragile (uses '' string check and mixes >0/0 tests) rather than explicit missing/string-trim checks.
No handling or exceptions for survey special codes (e.g., 97/98/99) in numeric range checks.
The script creates A1x4_itemFlag and immediately deletes it at the end, making it impossible to surface validation results; validation should produce persistent flag or call validation function.
instructions: Add the required sum validation call after computing SumA1x4: CompareNum3D('A1x4','=',f('S7')['4'].toNumber(),'defaults'); (or create an equivalent flag if CompareNum3D is unavailable).

Change the per-item numeric validity check to only validate non-missing values. Replace IF (MISS(x) OR ~RANGE(x,0,999)) A1x4_itemFlag = 1. with IF (NOT(MISS(x)) AND ~RANGE(x,0,999)) A1x4_itemFlag = 1.

Do not use SEL IF to enforce 'Other' text logic. Instead create a flag variable (e.g., A1x4_otherFlag):
  IF (A1x4_9 > 0 AND (MISSING(A1x4_9_other) OR RTRIM(LTRIM(A1x4_9_other)) = '')) A1x4_otherFlag = 1.
  IF ((A1x4_9 = 0 OR MISSING(A1x4_9)) AND (NOT(MISSING(A1x4_9_other)) AND RTRIM(LTRIM(A1x4_9_other)) <> '')) A1x4_otherFlag = 1.
This preserves cases and flags inconsistent data.

Treat special codes appropriately in the numeric checks. If 97/98/99 should be allowed as special/missing codes, modify the range test to exclude them, e.g.: IF (NOT(MISS(x)) AND (NOT(x IN (97,98,99))) AND ~RANGE(x,0,999)) A1x4_itemFlag = 1.

Keep validation flags (A1x4_itemFlag, A1x4_otherFlag, SumA1x4 compare flag) as persistent variables (do not DELETE them immediately) so validation results can be reported or used by RequireCheck3D/other processes.

root_causes: Per-item numeric check flags missing values as invalid (IF (MISS(x) OR ~RANGE(x,0,999)) ...) despite question being NotRequired
Flag variable A1x5_itemFlag is not initialized before the DO REPEAT and is overwritten on each iteration (risk of incorrect/leftover values)
No validation that the computed SumA1x5 equals the target f('S7')['5'] value — CompareNum3D/explicit comparison is not implemented in SPSS code
SEL IF is used to enforce consistency between A1x5_9 and its open-text field; this filters the dataset instead of flagging invalid cases
Other-text check uses direct equality to '' rather than robust string-empty testing (e.g. STRIP/LTRIM/RTRIM) and does not create a flag variable for review
Precision requirement (3 decimal places) is not enforced for the numeric cells
A1x5_itemFlag is deleted at the end which prevents reporting of item-level validation results
instructions: Do not treat missing item cells as invalid. Initialize a flag before the loop (e.g. COMPUTE A1x5_itemFlag = 0) and inside DO REPEAT only set the flag when a non-missing value is out of range: IF (NOT(MISSING(x)) AND (x < 0 OR x > 999)) A1x5_itemFlag = 1.
Initialize any additional flags before use (e.g. COMPUTE A1x5_sumFlag = 0. COMPUTE A1x5_otherFlag = 0) so results are deterministic.

Implement the required sum comparison: after computing SumA1x5, compare it to the S7 value and set a flag if they differ, e.g. IF (NOT MISSING(SumA1x5) AND NOT MISSING(S7_5) AND SumA1x5 <> S7_5) A1x5_sumFlag = 1. (Or call the CompareNum3D equivalent if available in the environment.)

Replace SEL IF with flagging logic for the open-text 'Other' check. For example: IF (A1x5_9 > 0 AND STRIP(A1x5_9_other) = '') A1x5_otherFlag = 1. IF ((A1x5_9 = 0 OR MISSING(A1x5_9)) AND STRIP(A1x5_9_other) <> '') A1x5_otherFlag = 1.
Use a robust string-empty test (STRIP or RTRIM/LTRIM) rather than direct comparison to ''. Ensure A1x5_9_other variable name matches the actual open-text variable name.
Enforce precision = 3 where required. For example, inside DO REPEAT add: IF (NOT MISSING(x) AND (ROUND(x,0.001) <> x)) A1x5_precisionFlag = 1.
Do not DELETE validation flag variables until after they have been used/reported. Remove the DELETE VARIABLES A1x5_itemFlag line or move it to after reporting/recording validation results.

Ensure variable names used in the sum-comparison reference the actual S7 field name in the dataset (e.g. S7_5). If the form-level Validate code uses f('S7')['5'], map that to the correct dataset variable and use it in the comparison.

root_causes: Script never assigns values to the required output variables HidA1ARPIS_1 .. HidA1ARPIS_5; it only computes temporary check variables and then deletes them.
Temporary check variables are deleted immediately, so no persistent derived variables remain for the question.
Subquestions 3–5 are not created/assigned; the script only duplicates hidA1arpis_chk2 into other temporaries but does not map those to HidA1ARPIS_3.._5.
No handling of special codes (e.g., 97, 98, 99) or explicit missing-value logic for source items.
Expected entry condition (isTest() show-only in test mode) is not represented in the script.
instructions: Compute and store results directly into the question's subvariables HidA1ARPIS_1 through HidA1ARPIS_5 instead of using temporary variables that are deleted. For example: COMPUTE HidA1ARPIS_1 = SUM(A1x3_53 A1x3_7 A1x3_54 A1x4_53 A1x4_7 A1x4_54 A1x5_53 A1x5_7 A1x5_54).

Compute HidA1ARPIS_2 as the SUM of codes 2+3+4+5+6+7 across A1x3_, A1x4_, and A1x5_ (list all variables explicitly), then assign HidA1ARPIS_3 = HidA1ARPIS_2, HidA1ARPIS_4 = HidA1ARPIS_2, and HidA1ARPIS_5 = HidA1ARPIS_2 (or compute separately if intended). Do not DELETE these HidA1ARPIS_* variables.
If intermediate temporaries are required, keep them only long enough to assign the HidA1ARPIS_* variables and then delete those temporaries (do not delete the HidA1ARPIS_* variables).

Add handling for special codes and missing-value logic: if any contributing source variable equals special codes (97, 98, 99) or is system-missing in a way that should invalidate the derived result, set the corresponding HidA1ARPIS_* to system-missing or apply the intended rule. Implement this with DO IF / ELSE IF blocks or conditional COMPUTE/RECODE as appropriate.

If the question should only be populated in test mode, wrap the derivation with the entry condition (isTest()) or an equivalent selection so the HidA1ARPIS_* variables are only computed when the entry condition is true.
Ensure the final variable names exactly match the expected output variable IDs (HidA1ARPIS_1 .. HidA1ARPIS_5) and that numeric formatting/precision is set elsewhere if required.

root_causes: Script only contains a title statement and has no validation or derivation logic implemented.
No selection/filter to identify missing or out-of-range responses (no sel if ...).
No validation that A3x1 values are within the expected answer codes 1–6.
No output/listing of respondent id and the variable for review (e.g., list respid, A3x1).
No handling or explicit decision about potential special codes (97, 98, 99) if applicable.
instructions:
Implement validation to select cases with missing or invalid codes. For example add:
temporary.
sel if miss(A3x1) or ~range(A3x1,1,6).

Add an output listing to inspect those cases, e.g.:
list respid A3x1.

If the project uses special codes (97/98/99), include them in the allowed set rather than flagging them as invalid. For example replace the selection with:
sel if miss(A3x1) or ~any(A3x1,1,2,3,4,5,6,97,98,99).
Ensure the variable name A3x1 is correct and consistent; add the temporary statement before sel if to avoid permanent filtering.

root_causes: No validation of allowed answer codes (expected codes 1–6) — script does not check for missing or out-of-range responses
No selection/filter to identify problematic records (missing or invalid) — the script simply lists all cases
No handling or mention of special codes (e.g. 97/98/99) if those apply — script does not consider them
instructions: Add a temporary selection that lists only missing or out-of-range responses for A3x2. For the expected answer set 1–6 use: temporary. sel if miss(A3x2) or ~range(A3x2,1,6). list respid A3x2.
If the survey uses special codes (97/98/99), include them in the valid range or adjust the selection to allow them (for example: sel if miss(A3x2) or ~any(A3x2,1,2,3,4,5,6,97,98,99)).
Ensure the validation logic matches precisely the intended valid codes (1–6) — do not omit the range check that identifies invalid or missing responses.

root_causes: Test-mode gating is incorrect: the script uses (SYSMIS(qTesting) OR qTesting = 1) which causes checks to run when the qTesting variable is missing (i.e. in production), whereas the expected logic requires test-mode-only execution (isTest()).
instructions: Restrict the checks to test mode only. Replace the gating condition IF ((SYSMIS(qTesting) OR qTesting = 1) AND ...) with a condition that evaluates true only in test mode, for example IF (NOT SYSMIS(qTesting) AND qTesting = 1 AND ...).
Alternatively, if an isTest() function/flag is available, use that directly (e.g. IF (isTest() AND ...) ...) so comparisons run only in test mode.
Ensure that if qTesting may not exist you do NOT default to running checks when it is missing; absence of a test flag should skip these test-only comparisons.

root_causes: Validation does not enforce the entry condition f('qSurveyType').none('2'). The script flags missing/invalid S8 for all cases regardless of qSurveyType.
instructions: Only validate S8 when the question was active per the entry condition (qSurveyType != '2').
Modify the selection to include the entry condition. Example: temporary. sel if (miss(qSurveyType) or qSurveyType <> 2) and (miss(S8) or ~range(S8,1,3)). list respid S8.
If you prefer strict check only when qSurveyType is present and not '2': sel if qSurveyType <> 2 and (miss(S8) or ~range(S8,1,3)).

root_causes: Validation does not enforce the entry condition f('qCountry').any('7'). The script flags missing/invalid S9DE for all respondents regardless of qCountry.
instructions: Only validate S9DE when qCountry == 7 (Germany) per the entry condition.
Change the selection to include the entry condition. Example: temporary. sel if qCountry = 7 and (miss(S9DE) or ~range(S9DE,1,16)). list respid S9DE.
If qCountry can be missing and you still want to avoid false positives, use: temporary. sel if (miss(qCountry) = 0 and qCountry = 7) and (miss(S9DE) or ~range(S9DE,1,16)).

root_causes: Does not enforce the entry condition that HidS7Vals > 0 before validating S7 items.
Missing the required validation CompareNumQues('S7','<=','HidS7Vals','S7') — there is no check that the sum of S7_1..S7_5 is <= HidS7Vals.
Validation only checks individual item ranges but not the aggregate constraint described in question_attributes.
instructions: Apply the entry condition so validation only runs when HidS7Vals > 0. For example, surround checks with a selection like: TEMPORARY. SELECT IF HidS7Vals > 0.

Add an aggregate check to ensure the sum of S7 items does not exceed HidS7Vals. For example: COMPUTE S7_total = SUM(S7_1 TO S7_5). TEMPORARY. SELECT IF S7_total > HidS7Vals. LIST respid S7_total S7_1 TO S7_5.
Keep the existing per-item range checks (0 to 999) but run them only when HidS7Vals > 0 (see first instruction).
After adding the sum check, delete any helper variables (e.g., S7_total) if needed: DELETE VARIABLES S7_total.

root_causes: Does not enforce the entry condition: the checks run for all cases instead of only when HidS7Vals > 0 (GreaterThan('HidS7Vals',0).size() > 0).
Missing the validation CompareNumQues('S7','<=','HidS7Vals','S7') — there is no check that the sum/total of S7 items is <= HidS7Vals.
Does not handle numeric precision requirements (Precision = 3) — no check for allowed decimal precision.
Potentially flags missing values even when the question should not be shown (because entry condition not applied).
instructions: Restrict validation to respondents for whom the question is shown. Add the entry-condition check before listing, e.g. only run the temporary selection when HidS7Vals > 0 (e.g. sel if HidS7Vals > 0 and (miss(v) or v < 0 or v > 999)).

Implement the CompareNumQues validation: compute a temporary sum variable, e.g. COMPUTE sumS7 = SUM(S7_1, S7_2, S7_3, S7_4, S7_5). Then flag/list cases where sumS7 > HidS7Vals (only when HidS7Vals > 0).
If decimal precision must be enforced (Precision = 3), add a check for the number of decimal places (or allowable rounding) for each S7_* and flag values with more than 3 decimal places.
Keep the existing lower/upper bounds (v < 0 or v > 999) but ensure these are only applied when the question is displayed (HidS7Vals > 0) to avoid false positives.

root_causes: Entry condition isTest() is not enforced; the check will run for all respondents instead of only in test mode as expected.
Computed hidS7_chk defaults to 2 which will incorrectly label cases when S7_1 is missing (should treat missing explicitly) — no explicit handling for S7_1 missing or invalid values.
instructions: Run the diagnostic only in test mode. Wrap the temporary selection with the entry condition isTest(), e.g. sel if isTest() and (miss(hidS7) or ~range(hidS7,1,2) or (hidS7_chk <> hidS7)).

Compute hidS7_chk defensively: initialize hidS7_chk = SYSMIS, then set hidS7_chk = 1 if S7_1 = 0, set hidS7_chk = 2 if S7_1 > 0. This prevents misclassification when S7_1 is missing or invalid. Example: COMPUTE hidS7_chk = $SYSMIS. IF (S7_1 = 0) hidS7_chk = 1. IF (S7_1 > 0) hidS7_chk = 2.
Then compare hidS7 to hidS7_chk and list cases where hidS7 is missing/out-of-range or differs from the computed value, but only when isTest() is true.

root_causes: Does not apply the entry condition f('qSurveyType').none('2') — validation runs for all respondents instead of excluding qSurveyType = 2.
instructions: Restrict the validation to respondents for whom the question is shown. Add the entry condition to the selection, e.g. sel if (qSurveyType <> 2) and (miss(S8) or ~range(S8,1,3)).
Keep the existing range check for allowed codes 1–3, but ensure it only runs when qSurveyType is not '2' to avoid false positives.

root_causes: Does not enforce the entry condition f('qCountry').any('7') — checks run for all respondents instead of only when qCountry = 7.
instructions: Apply the entry condition so the validation only runs when qCountry = 7. For example: sel if (qCountry = 7) and (miss(S9DE) or ~range(S9DE,1,16)).
Keep the existing range check for codes 1–16, but scope it to respondents with qCountry = 7 to avoid flagging respondents from other countries.
